04201nam a22006015i 9780804792325DE-B159720200915044058.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200915t20202014cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047923257 a10.1515/97808047923252doi  a(DE-B1597)563929  a(OCoLC)1198930928  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aHIS0260002bisacsh04a962.052231 aBrand, Laurie A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aOfficial Stories :bPolitics and National Narratives in Egypt and Algeria /cLaurie A. Brand. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©2014  a1 online resource (296 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStanford Studies in Middle Eastern and Islamic Societies and Cultures00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPreface -- tA Note on Qawmiyya and Wataniyya -- tAcronyms -- t1 Restor(y)ing the State: National Narratives and Regime Resilience -- t2 Egypt under Nasser: The Evolution of Revolution -- t3 Egypt under Sadat and Mubarak: Rescripting Revolution, Redefining Legitimacy -- t4 Algeria from the Liberation Struggle through Boumedienne: Historic to Revolutionary Legitimacy -- t5 Algeria from Bendjedid to the Dark Decade: The Narrative Fractures -- t6 Narrative Rescriptings and Legitimacy Crises -- tEpilogue. The Official Narrative and the "Arab Spring": The Limits of Revolution -- tNotes -- tSelect Bibliography -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aUntil the recent uprisings in the Middle East and North Africa, the resilience of authoritarian regimes seemed a fundamental feature of regional politics. While economic, political, and internal security policies are most often considered in discussions of regime maintenance, Laurie Brand introduces a new factor, that of national narratives. Portrayals of a country's founding, identity, and bases of unity can be a powerful strategy in sustaining a ruling elite. Brand argues that such official stories, which are used to reinforce the right to rule, justify policies, or combat opponents, deserve careful exploration if we are to understand the full range of tools available to respond to crises that threaten a leadership's hold on power. Brand examines more than six decades of political, economic, and military challenges in two of North Africa's largest countries: Egypt and Algeria. Through a careful analysis of various texts-history and religion textbooks, constitutions, national charters, and presidential speeches-Official Stories demonstrates how leaderships have attempted to reconfigure narratives to confront challenges to their power. Brand's account also demonstrates how leaderships may miscalculate, thereby setting in motion opposition forces beyond their control.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 4aAlgeria. 4aEgypt. 4adiscourse. 4aeconomic crises. 4afounding story. 4alegitimacy. 4anational identity. 4anational narrative. 4apolitical crises. 4apolitical transition. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311070398640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080479232540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804792325423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804792325.jpg  a978-3-11-070398-6  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles